<br>
Let me try to answer some of the questions, before MaiMai Panda gets here, and gives the really GOOD answer that I wish I could write. *wink*<br>
<br>
There are 4 Japanese alphabets:<br>
1) ABCs, called ROMAJI...these are used for some easy-to-understand full-length foreign words, and for abbreviations for imported words, like VTR (video tape recorder), CM (commercial) and CD (compact disk).<br>
<br>
2) KATA-KANA is alot like ITALICS, in English.  It's used for foreign words, or when you have some special reason for wanting to make the word look different from its usual meaning.  Katakana is a GREAT place to start, when you're learnign Japanese, because so many English words are spelled in Katakana.  It's an instant adrenalin-injection into your vocabulary !<br>
<br>
Some people really HATE the kanji-characters used to spell their names.  These people may be Japanese, but spell their names in Katakana to make them sound cool &amp; foreign, or to hide the kanji implications.  To explain:  Kanji carry a meaning BEYOND the sound.  They're basically little pictures of things, like a sketch of a tree or a big eye.  If your name is made up of unflattering kanji, you might want to change it a little, and refer only to the SOUND of your name.  The closest European equivalent I can think of is, if you were saddled from birth with the name &quot;lipschitz&quot; or &quot;Blunden&quot;, you might want to change the name to &quot;licious&quot; or &quot;London&quot;....to change the implied meaning, without completely erasing the original name.<br>
<br>
Brand-names do this intentionally, sometimes, to make their products sound LESS Japanese.  For example, SUZUKI motorbike company rarely writes its name in KANJI (meaning = bell + tree), preferring to use the foreign-cool looking spellings in ROMAJI or KATAKANA.<br>
<br>
This can work in reverse, too, where a foreign word is usually spelled in KATAKANA, but for some playful or poetic reason, has earned a KANJI spelling, too.  For example, AMERICA would often be spelled with KATAKANA, but is also often written with the KANJI characters for &quot;rice + country&quot;.  <br>
<br>
<br>
3) KANJI is little pictures of IDEAS and CONCEPTS.  These aren't phonetic... the picture is of an idea, like &quot;BALL&quot;, and could have several different pronunciations like &quot;BALL, MARBLE, ORB, BEAD&quot;.... you get the idea.<br>
So, these are great for distinguishing the MEANING of a word, but are truly horrible when you don't already know the symbol you're looking at.  Kanji are the major stumbling block for non-Chinese foreigners trying to learn Japanese.  There are THOUSANDS of Kanji, each possession an average of 2 pronunciations.<br>
The good news is, after you know roughly 800, the rest are practically never used.<br>
<br>
If you want to know some good books for learning Kanji, post about it, and we'll recommend some.  Don't expect much good advice about learning Kanji, FROM a Japanese person, though... most Japanese learned Kanji while in grammar school, through a process of repetition.  So, it's often true that a Japanese guy can write a character, but can't tell you what the various small sketches in the character are supposed to be sketches OF.<br>
<br>
4) HIRAGANA is, like Katakana, based on the SOUND of words, not their MEANING.  It's therefore alot like our ABCs, except that Katakana and Hiragana go by SYLLABLES, so &quot;BA&quot; (for example) would be 1 letter, not 2.  Hiragana is often written in very small characters above difficult Kanji... especially in childrens' books, and in dictionaries, or if the kanji is a rare and difficult-to-pronounce-or-remember one.  These hiragana hints-to-pronunciation are called FURIGANA or RUBY (because they're usually written in RUBY-red ink).<br>
<br>
For really advanced learners of Japanese, there's a magazine-for-adult-readers called &quot;Furigana Times&quot;, where all the kanji have furigana written above them, so foreigners can puzzle out the pronunciations.<br>
<br>
Hiragana is usually used NOT for FURIGANA, but rather to a) spell out VERY common words, <br>
b) label different parts of a sentence based on the rules of grammar,<br>
c) and for endings to Kanji words like the -ED at the end of PAINTED.  <br>
<br>
So, for example, if I wanted to say &quot;I painted HIROSHIMA on the side of John's car,&quot; I'd write it like this:<br>
WATAKUSHI (in kanji, meaning = I)<br>
HA (in hiragana, meaning &quot;this's th'subject o'the sentence)<br>
JON (katakana, since it's a foreign word = &quot;JOHN&quot;)<br>
SAN (hiragana, meaning = Mr.)<br>
NO (hiragana, meaning   = 's  )<br>
KURUMA (kanji, meaning = car)<br>
NI (or DE, in hiragana, meaning = at or on)<br>
HIROSHIMA (in kanji or katakana, depending on whether I mean the city or the nuclear event)<br>
WO (in hiragana, meaning &quot;this's th'direct object o'th'sentence)<br>
KAKIMASHITA (KA would be in kanji, meaning = write or paint, and the rest of this verb would be in Hiragana meaning = polite-form-of-verb  + -ed)<br>
<br>
So, as you can see, a single sentence can have all the different alphabets, and a single word often has both kanji and hiragana.<br>
=============<br>
It's worth explaining how &amp; why a word might be spelled several different ways, to show different meanings.  For example, the city-name HIROSHIMA would be spelled in KANJI if you're referring to the city, and in KATAKANA if you're trying to refer to the first A-bomb dropped on civilians, like in a poster readign &quot;No More HIROSHIMAs !&quot;.  You might spell Hiroshima in Hiragana if your intended audience is (no offense) foreigners or small children.<br>
<br>
Lastly, sometimes, a Kanji word is written in hiragana just to show some variant pronunciation... sort of like when a novelist intentionally spells &quot;what do you want ?!&quot; as whaddaya wan' ?!&quot; For more about this, you could look at amazon dot com for &quot;manga-zine&quot; books about how to learn Japanese through reading comic books. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/11/03 2:47 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1183.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: the several Japanese alphabets</span><hr size=1> *bows down* <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Mamonaku. 11ban sen ni  Panda densha ga mairimasu. </span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> <!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--> <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;">Abunai desu kara, kiiro no sen no uchigawa made osagarikudasai.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->  </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> </strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
